es bones to style itself.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Heatmor}} Heatmor\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30af\u30a4\u30bf\u30e9\u30f3|Kuitaran}}\n|align=center| {{nts|631}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#f08030; text-align:center;\"| Fire\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|Heatmor will try to burn through Durant's weak armor and then eat it.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Durant}} Durant\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30a2\u30a4\u30a2\u30f3\u30c8|Aianto}}\n|align=center| {{nts|632}}\n| style=\"background:#a8b820; text-align:center;\"| Bug\n| style=\"background:#b8b8d0; text-align:center;\"| Steel\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|It tries to size up and defend itself against Heatmor.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Deino}} Deino\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30e2\u30ce\u30ba|Monozu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|633}}\n| style=\"background:#5c483b; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dark}}\n| style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n|align=center| [[#Zweilous|Zweilous (#634)]]\n|Deino, derived from \"one\" in German, is blind so it usually bites things and comes out with scratches.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Zweilous}} Zweilous\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30b8\u30d8\u30c3\u30c9|Jiheddo}}\n|align=center| {{nts|634}}\n|  style=\"background:#5c483b; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dark}}\n|  style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n|align=center| [[#Hydreigon|Hydreigon (#635)]]\n|Zweilous, derived from \"two\" in German, has two heads which fight over food a lot.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Hydreigon}} Hydreigon\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30b5\u30b6\u30f3\u30c9\u30e9|Sazandora}}\n|align=center| {{nts|635}}\n| style=\"background:#5c483b; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dark}}\n| style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|Hydreigon, derived from \"three\" in German and dragon, has three heads. Before it evolves, the heads fight to determine who will be the dominant head.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Larvesta}} Larvesta\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30e1\u30e9\u30eb\u30d0|Meraruba}}\n|align=center| {{nts|636}}\n| style=\"background:#a8b820; text-align:center;\"| Bug\n| style=\"background:#f08030; text-align:center;\"| Fire\n|align=center| [[#Volcarona|Volcarona (#637)]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Volcarona}} Volcarona\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30a6\u30eb\u30ac\u30e2\u30b9|Urugamosu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|637}}\n| style=\"background:#a8b820; text-align:center;\"| Bug\n| style=\"background:#f08030; text-align:center;\"| Fire\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Cobalion}} Cobalion\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30b3\u30d0\u30eb\u30aa\u30f3|Kobaruon}}\n|align=center| {{nts|638}}\n| style=\"background:#b8b8d0; text-align:center;\"| Steel\n| style=\"background:#94352d; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Fighting}}\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Cobalion's design is inspired by [[Athos (character)|Athos]] from ''[[The Three Musketeers]]''.<ref name=\"GR_trvia\">{{cite web|author=Henry Gilbert|work=[[GamesRadar]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=October 14, 2012|accessdate=January 27, 2016|title=Pok\u00e9mon facts - 30 little known pieces of trivia from the classic franchise|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/pokemon-facts-15-little-known-things-about-classic-franchise/}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Terrakion}} Terrakion\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30c6\u30e9\u30ad\u30aa\u30f3|Terakion}}\n|align=center| {{nts|639}}\n| style=\"background:#b8a038; text-align:center;\"| Rock\n| style=\"background:#94352d; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Fighting}}\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Terrakion's design is inspired by [[Porthos]] from ''The Three Musketeers''.<ref name=\"GR_trvia\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Virizion}} Virizion\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30d3\u30ea\u30b8\u30aa\u30f3|Birijion}}\n|align=center| {{nts|640}}\n| style=\"background:#2dcd45; text-align:center;\"| Grass\n| style=\"background:#94352d; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Fighting}}\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Virizion's design is inspired by [[Aramis]] from ''The Three Musketeers''.<ref name=\"GR_trvia\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Tornadus}} Tornadus\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30c8\u30eb\u30cd\u30ed\u30b9|Torunerosu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|641}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#a890f0; text-align:center;\"| Flying\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Tornadus' \"Incarnate Forme\" is inspired by the Japanese [[F\u016bjin]], the [[Shinto]] God of the wind. Its \"Therian Forme\" stems from the [[Four Symbols (China)|Four Symbols]] of Chinese myth, specifically the [[Vermilion Bird]]. It is capable of transforming between forms via an item called the \"Reveal Glass\".<ref name=\"GR_myth\"/><ref name=\"RevealGlass\"/> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Thundurus}} Thundurus\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30dc\u30eb\u30c8\u30ed\u30b9|Borutorosu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|642}}\n| style=\"background:#f8d030; text-align:center;\"| Electric\n| style=\"background:#a890f0; text-align:center;\"| Flying\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Thundurus' \"Incarnate Forme\" is inspired by the Japanese [[Raijin]], the Shinto God of lightning, thunder, and storms. Its \"Therian Forme\" stems from the Four Symbols of Chinese myth, specifically the [[Azure Dragon]]. It is capable of transforming between forms via an item called the \"Reveal Glass\".<ref name=\"GR_myth\"/><ref name=\"RevealGlass\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Reshiram}} Reshiram\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30ec\u30b7\u30e9\u30e0|Reshiramu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|643}}\n| style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n| style=\"background:#f08030; text-align:center;\"| Fire\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Zekrom}} Zekrom\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30bc\u30af\u30ed\u30e0|Zekuromu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|644}}\n| style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n| style=\"background:#f8d030; text-align:center;\"| Electric\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|It powers up with electricity from its tail. \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Landorus}} Landorus\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u30ed\u30b9|Randorosu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|645}}\n| style=\"background:#e0c068; text-align:center;\"| Ground\n| style=\"background:#a890f0; text-align:center;\"| Flying\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Landorus' \"Incarnate Forme\" is inspired by the Japanese [[Inari \u014ckami]], the Shinto God of agriculture and fertility. Its \"Therian Forme\" stems from the Four Symbols of Chinese myth, specifically the [[White Tiger (China)|White Tiger]]. It is capable of transforming between forms via an item called the \"Reveal Glass\".<ref name=\"GR_myth\"/><ref name=\"RevealGlass\">{{cite video game|title=''[[Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire|Pok\u00e9mon Omega Ruby]]''|developer=[[Game Freak]]|publisher=[[The Pok\u00e9mon Company]]|date=April 23, 2015|platform=[[Nintendo 3DS]]|version=1.4|quote='''Reveal Glass description''': 'A looking glass that reveals the truth. It's a mysterious glass that returns a Pok\u00e9mon to its original shape.'}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Kyurem}} Kyurem\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30ad\u30e5\u30ec\u30e0|Kyuremu}}\n|align=center| {{nts|646}}\n| style=\"background:#700aee; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Dragon}}\n| style=\"background:#98d8d8; text-align:center;\"| Ice\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Capable of fusing with either Reshiram or Zekrom to become \"White Kyurem\" or \"Black Kyurem\", respectively.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Keldeo}} Keldeo\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30b1\u30eb\u30c7\u30a3\u30aa|Kerudio}}\n|align=center| {{nts|647}}\n| style=\"background:#149eff; text-align:center;\"| Water\n| style=\"background:#94352d; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Fighting}}\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n| Keldeo's design is inspired by [[Charles de Batz-Castelmore d'Artagnan|d'Artagnan]] from ''The Three Musketeers''.<ref name=\"GR_trvia\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| {{anchor|Meloetta}} Meloetta\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| {{nihongo||\u30e1\u30ed\u30a8\u30c3\u30bf|Meroetta}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{nts|648}}\n| style=\"background:#a8a878; text-align:center;\"| Normal\n| style=\"background:#ff6996; text-align:center;\"| Psychic\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#ececec; vertical-align:middle; font-size:smaller; text-align:center;\" class=\"table-na\"| Does not evolve\n| \"Aria Forme\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#a8a878; text-align:center;\"| Normal\n| style=\"background:#94352d; text-align:center;\"| {{font color|white|Fighting}}\n| \"Pirouette Forme\"\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{anchor|Genesect}} Genesect\n!scope=\"row\"| {{nihongo||\u30b2\u30ce\u30bb\u30af\u30c8|Genosekuto}}\n|align=center| {{nts|649}}\n| style=\"background:#a8b820; text-align:center;\"| Bug\n| style=\"background:#b8b8d0; text-align:center;\"| Steel\n| {{n/a|Does not evolve}}\n|It was altered by Team Plasma after it was revived.\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Pok\u00e9mon directory|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of generation V Pok\u00e9mon}}\n[[Category:Lists of Pok\u00e9mon]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "2600:387:0:803::74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eList of Pok\u00e9mon)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_generation_V_Pok%C3%A9mon"}
{"title_page": "1999 Alabama Crimson Tide football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season|sport=football\n  |year=1999\n  |team=Alabama Crimson Tide\n  <!-- Commented out: |image=AL angry elephant logo.png -->\n  |conference=Southeastern Conference\n  |division=Western Division\n  |short_conf=SEC\n  |CoachRank=8\n  |APRank=8\n  |record=10\u20133\n  |conf_record=7\u20131\n  |head_coach=[[Mike DuBose]]\n  |hc_year = 3rd\n  |captain = {{Collapsible list\n   |title=5\n   |1=Shaun Alexander\n   |2=Cornelius Griffin\n   |3=Miguel Merritt\n   |4=Ryan Pflunger\n   |5=Chris Samuels\n}}\n  |off_coach=[[Neil Callaway]] (2nd year as OC 3rd overall)\n  | cooff_coach1=[[Charlie Stubbs (American football)|Charlie Stubbs]]\n  | cooc1_year=2nd\n  |def_coach= [[Ellis Johnson (American football coach)|Ellis Johnson]] (3rd year)\n  |off_scheme=\n  |def_scheme=\n  |stadium=[[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 83,818)<br>[[Legion Field]]<br>(Capacity: 83,091)\n  |champion=SEC champion<br>SEC Western Division champion\n  |bowl=[[2000 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result=L 34\u201335 <sup>OT</sup> vs. [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n  |conf_champ= [[1999 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]]\n  |conf_champ_result= W 34\u20137 vs. [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n}}\n{{1999 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''1999 Alabama Crimson Tide football team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] in the [[1999 NCAA Division I-A football season|1999 college football season]]. The team was led by head coach [[Mike DuBose]], who was in his third season with the program. The [[Alabama Crimson Tide|Crimson Tide]], also known informally as the Tide, played their home games at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]], in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]], and [[Legion Field]], in [[Birmingham, Alabama]].\n\nThe team entered the season trying to build upon a 7\u20135 record from their [[1998 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1998 season]]. The 1999 team had tremendous success. After a stunning last second loss to [[1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]] early in the year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1648768| title=Louisiana Tech has history of comebacks|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=October 23, 2003|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> they eventually finished with a 9\u20132 regular season record (7\u20131 in the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]). This included defeating [[1999 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] on the road for the first time ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/news/1999/11/20/alabama_auburn_ap/|title=Atlanta-bound Alabama: Tide secure SEC West crown with 28\u201317 victory| work=[[Sports Illustrated]]| date=November 21, 1999|accessdate=September 26, 2008}}</ref> The team went on to the [[1999 SEC Championship Game]] where they defeated [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] for the second time for the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/05/sports/college-football-alabama-beats-florida-in-the-sec-title-game.html|title=Alabama Beats Florida In the S.E.C. Title Game|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 5, 1999|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> Alabama played [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] in the [[2000 Orange Bowl]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alabama to make 50th bowl appearance|work=[[The Crimson White]]|date=December 6, 1999}}</ref> and suffered a 35\u201334 loss in overtime, due to a missed [[extra point]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores100/100001/100001322.htm|title=Michigan vs. Alabama|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=January 1, 2000|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> Alabama had beaten Florida during the regular season by a single point in overtime, also due to a missed extra point.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/03/sports/college-football-2d-point-after-is-the-difference.html|title=2nd Point After Is the Difference|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 3, 1999|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1999\n| poll = AP\n| timezone = Central\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 4\n| time = 11:30 a.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 20\n| opponent = [[1999 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]\n| site_stadium = [[Vanderbilt Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville, TN]]\n| tv = [[Jefferson Pilot Sports|JPS]]\n| score = 28\u201317\n| attend = 41,600\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 11\n| time = 11:30 a.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 21\n| opponent = [[1999 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]]\n| site_stadium = [[Legion Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham, AL]]\n| tv = JPS\n| score = 37\u201310\n| attend = 80,110\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 18\n| time = 4:00 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 18\n| opponent = [[1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]]\n| site_stadium = Legion Field\n| site_cityst = Birmingham, AL\n| tv = [[Pay-per-view|PPV]]\n| score = 28\u201329\n| attend = 80,312\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 25\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1999 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]]\n| opprank = 14\n| site_stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa, AL]]\n| tv = [[SEC on CBS|CBS]]\n| score = 35\u201328\n| attend = 83,818\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 2\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 21\n| opponent = [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n| opprank = 3\n| site_stadium = [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville, FL]]\n| tv = CBS\n| score = 40\u201339\n| overtime = OT\n| attend = 85,721\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 16\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l =