rst=Kenny|last=Smith|pos=DT|link=y}}\n| special_teams_players=\n\n}}\n{{American football roster/Footer|roster_url=http://tidentenn.com/1999FootballRoster.htm\n| head_coach = *[[Mike DuBose]]\n| asst_coach = \n| accessdate=\n}}\n\n==Game summaries==\n\n===Vanderbilt===\n{{See also|1999 Vanderbilt Commodores football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#20 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=7\n|R4=14\n|Home=Commodores\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=10\n|H4=0\n}}\n[[Shaun Alexander]] scored the final two touchdowns in the 4th quarter to rally Alabama to a season opening road win over Vanderbilt.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Houston===\n{{See also|1999 Houston Cougars football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=Cougars\n|R1=3\n|R2=0\n|R3=7\n|R4=0\n|Home='''#21 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=10\n|H2=7\n|H3=6\n|H4=14\n}}\nAlabama would go over 500 yards of offense for just the second time in the Mike Dubose era and win convincingly over Houston. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Louisiana Tech===\n{{See also|1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''Bulldogs'''\n|R1=6\n|R2=6\n|R3=3\n|R4=14\n|Home=#18 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=3\n|H3=15\n|H4=10\n}}\nBack-up quarterback Brian Stallworth would find Sean Cangelosi in the end zone with two seconds left to upset Alabama for the second time in three years. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Arkansas===\n{{See also|1999 Arkansas Razorbacks football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=#14 Razorbacks\n|R1=10\n|R2=3\n|R3=8\n|R4=7\n|Home='''Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=7\n|H2=7\n|H3=14\n|H4=7\n}}\nDespite turning the football over six times, Alabama would manage to hold on and upset #14 Arkansas at Bryant-Denny Stadium. This would be the first time under Mike Dubose Alabama beat a ranked opponent.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Florida===\n{{See also|1999 Florida Gators football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#21 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=3\n|R2=10\n|R3=6\n|R4=14\n|R5=7\n|Home=#3 Gators\n|H1=7\n|H2=0\n|H3=15\n|H4=11\n|H5=6\n}}\nThe Crimson Tide snapped No. 3 Florida's 30-game winning streak at The Swamp on Saturday when Chris Kemp got a second chance on an extra-point attempt in overtime and drilled it.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Ole Miss===\n{{See also|1999 Ole Miss Rebels football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#11 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=10\n|R2=7\n|R3=10\n|R4=3\n|Home=#22 Rebels\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=10\n|H4=7\n}}\nDespite having a 27-7 lead midway through the third quarter, Alabama had to hold on late to beat Ole Miss. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Tennessee===\n{{See also|1999 Tennessee Volunteers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#5 Volunteers'''\n\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=7\n|R4=7\n|Home=#10 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=0\n|H4=0\n}}\nFor the first time since 1930, the [[Third Saturday in October]] would be in Tuscaloosa. Despite having the largest crowd ever to watch a football game in the state of Alabama to date, The Crimson Tide could not generate enough offense to beat Tennessee. This gave the Volunteers their fifth win in a row against Alabama.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Southern Miss===\n{{See also|1999 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road= #20 Golden Eagles\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=0\n|R4=7\n|Home='''#14 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=10\n|H2=10\n|H3=15\n|H4=0\n}}\nBehind the Alabama defense who would hold Southern Miss to -13 yards rushing, Alabama would generate enough points with a pick six and a punt return to beat Southern Miss for the eight year in a row. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===LSU===\n{{See also|1999 LSU Tigers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=Tigers\n|R1=7\n|R2=0\n|R3=7\n|R4=3\n|Home='''#12 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=10\n|H3=13\n|H4=0\n}}\nThe 1999 version of a Goal Line stand as Alabama would deny LSU quarterback Josh Booty of a potential game winning touchdown run by knocking him down six inches short of the end zone to win.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Mississippi State===\n{{See also|1999 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=#8 Bulldogs\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=0\n|R4=0\n|Home='''#11 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=3\n|H2=7\n|H3=3\n|H4=6\n}}\nWith the help of three Mississippi State interceptions, Alabama would end their three game losing streak to the Bulldogs and be one win away from winning the SEC West. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Auburn===\n{{See also|1999 Auburn Tigers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#8 Crimson Tide '''\n|R1=6\n|R2=0\n|R3=2\n|R4=20\n|Home=Tigers\n|H1=0\n|H2=14\n|H3=0\n|H4=3\n}}\n[[Shaun Alexander]] scored all three of Alabama touchdowns in the fourth quarter as the Crimson Tide rallied back for the second year in a row to beat Auburn. This would also be the first time Alabama won at [[Jordan-Hare Stadium]]. With the win, Alabama clinched the SEC West for the first time since 1996. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Florida===\n{{See also|1999 Florida Gators football team|1999 SEC Championship Game}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Title=[[SEC Championship Game]]\n|Road=#5 Gators\n|R1=7\n|R2=0\n|R3=0\n|R4=0\n|Home= '''#7 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=12\n|H3=3\n|H4=19\n}}\nAlabama used 34 unanswered points to beat Florida for the second time in 1999. This would be the Crimson Tide's first [[SEC Championship]] since 1992. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Michigan===\n{{See also|1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|2000 Orange Bowl}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Title=[[Orange Bowl]]\n|Road='''#8 Wolverines'''\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=21\n|R4=0\n|R5=7\n|Home= #5 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=14\n|H3=14\n|H4=0\n|H5=6\n}}\nDespite holding a 14 point lead in the third quarter, Alabama could not hold on and would lose in Overtime on a missed extra point by Ryan Pflugner. \n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1999 Southeastern Conference football season|Alabama]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football seasons]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1999 in sports in Alabama|Alabama Crimson Tide football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season|sport=football\n  |year=1999\n  |team=Alabama Crimson Tide\n  <!-- Commented out: |image=AL angry elephant logo.png -->\n  |conference=Southeastern Conference\n  |division=Western Division\n  |short_conf=SEC\n  |CoachRank=8\n  |APRank=8\n  |record=10\u20133\n  |conf_record=7\u20131\n  |head_coach=[[Mike DuBose]]\n  |hc_year = 3rd\n  |captain = {{Collapsible list\n   |title=5\n   |1=Shaun Alexander\n   |2=Cornelius Griffin\n   |3=Miguel Merritt\n   |4=Ryan Pflunger\n   |5=Chris Samuels\n}}\n  |off_coach=[[Neil Callaway]] (2nd year as OC 3rd overall)\n  | cooff_coach1=[[Charlie Stubbs (American football)|Charlie Stubbs]]\n  | cooc1_year=2nd\n  |def_coach= [[Ellis Johnson (American football coach)|Ellis Johnson]] (3rd year)\n  |off_scheme=\n  |def_scheme=\n  |stadium=[[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 83,818)<br>[[Legion Field]]<br>(Capacity: 83,091)\n  |champion=SEC champion<br>SEC Western Division champion\n  |bowl=[[2000 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result=L 34\u201335 <sup>OT</sup> vs. [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n  |conf_champ= [[1999 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]]\n  |conf_champ_result= W 34\u20137 vs. [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n}}\n{{1999 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''1999 Alabama Crimson Tide football team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] in the [[1999 NCAA Division I-A football season|1999 college football season]]. The team was led by head coach [[Mike DuBose]], who was in his third season with the program. The [[Alabama Crimson Tide|Crimson Tide]], also known informally as the Tide, played their home games at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]], in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]], and [[Legion Field]], in [[Birmingham, Alabama]].\n\nThe team entered the season trying to build upon a 7\u20135 record from their [[1998 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|1998 season]]. The 1999 team had tremendous success. After a stunning last second loss to [[1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]] early in the year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1648768| title=Louisiana Tech has history of comebacks|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=October 23, 2003|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> they eventually finished with a 9\u20132 regular season record (7\u20131 in the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]). This included defeating [[1999 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] on the road for the first time ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/news/1999/11/20/alabama_auburn_ap/|title=Atlanta-bound Alabama: Tide secure SEC West crown with 28\u201317 victory| work=[[Sports Illustrated]]| date=November 21, 1999|accessdate=September 26, 2008}}</ref> The team went on to the [[1999 SEC Championship Game]] where they defeated [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] for the second time for the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/05/sports/college-football-alabama-beats-florida-in-the-sec-title-game.html|title=Alabama Beats Florida In the S.E.C. Title Game|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 5, 1999|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> Alabama played [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] in the [[2000 Orange Bowl]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alabama to make 50th bowl appearance|work=[[The Crimson White]]|date=December 6, 1999}}</ref> and suffered a 35\u201334 loss in overtime, due to a missed [[extra point]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores100/100001/100001322.htm|title=Michigan vs. Alabama|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=January 1, 2000|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref> Alabama had beaten Florida during the regular season by a single point in overtime, also due to a missed extra point.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/03/sports/college-football-2d-point-after-is-the-difference.html|title=2nd Point After Is the Difference|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 3, 1999|accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1999\n| poll = AP\n| timezone = Central\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 4\n| time = 11:30 a.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 20\n| opponent = [[1999 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]]\n| site_stadium = [[Vanderbilt Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville, TN]]\n| tv = [[Jefferson Pilot Sports|JPS]]\n| score = 28\u201317\n| attend = 41,600\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 11\n| time = 11:30 a.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 21\n| opponent = [[1999 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]]\n| site_stadium = [[Legion Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham, AL]]\n| tv = JPS\n| score = 37\u201310\n| attend = 80,110\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 18\n| time = 4:00 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 18\n| opponent = [[1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]]\n| site_stadium = Legion Field\n| site_cityst = Birmingham, AL\n| tv = [[Pay-per-view|PPV]]\n| score = 28\u201329\n| attend = 80,312\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 25\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1999 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]]\n| opprank = 14\n| site_stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa, AL]]\n| tv = [[SEC on CBS|CBS]]\n| score = 35\u201328\n| attend = 83,818\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 2\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 21\n| opponent = [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n| opprank = 3\n| site_stadium = [[Ben Hill Griffin Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville, FL]]\n| tv = CBS\n| score = 40\u201339\n| overtime = OT\n| attend = 85,721\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 16\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 11\n| opponent = [[1999 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]]\n| opprank = 22\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013Ole Miss football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Vaught\u2013Hemingway Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Oxford, Mississippi|Oxford, MS]]\n| tv = CBS\n| score = 30\u201324\n| attend = 52,122\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 23\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| rank = 10\n| opponent = [[1999 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]]\n| opprank = 5\n| gamename = [[Third Saturday in October]]\n| site_stadium = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| site_cityst = Tuscaloosa, AL\n| tv = CBS\n| score = 7\u201321\n| attend = 86,869\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 30\n| time = 2:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| homecoming = y\n| rank = 14\n| opponent = [[1999 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team|Southern Miss]]\n| opprank = 20\n| site_stadium = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| site_cityst = Tuscaloosa, AL\n| tv = PPV\n| score = 35\u201314\n| attend = 83,818\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 6\n| time = 11:30 a.m.\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 12\n| opponent = [[1999 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013LSU football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| site_cityst = Tuscaloosa, AL\n| tv = JPS\n| score = 23\u201317\n| attend = 83,818\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 13\n| time = 2:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 11\n| opponent = [[1999 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]]\n| opprank = 8\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium\n| site_cityst = Tuscaloosa, AL\n| tv = CBS\n| score = 19\u20137\n| attend = 83,818\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 20\n| time = 6:30 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = [[1999 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]\n| gamename = [[Iron Bowl]]\n| site_stadium = [[Jordan\u2013Hare Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Auburn, Alabama|Auburn, AL]]\n| tv = [[ESPN]]\n| score = 28\u201317\n| attend = 85,214\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 4\n| time = 7:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| rank = 7\n| opponent = [[1999 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n| opprank = 5\n| gamename = [[1999 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]]\n| site_stadium = [[Georgia Dome]]\n| site_cityst = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, GA]]\n| tv = [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]]\n| score = 34\u20137\n| attend = 74,309\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = January 1, 2000\n| time = 7:30 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| neutral = y\n| rank = 5\n| opponent = [[1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n| opprank = 8\n| gamename = [[2000 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n| site_stadium = [[Pro Player Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Miami Gardens, Florida|Miami, Gardens, FL]]\n| tv = ABC\n| score = 34\u201335\n| overtime = OT\n| attend = 70,461\n}}\n}}\n\n==Roster==\n{{American football roster/Header\n| year = \t1999\n| team = Alabama Crimson Tide\n| teamcolors = y\n| offensive_players=\n{{American football roster/Player|num=37|class=Sr|first=Shaun|last=Alexander|pos=RB|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=80|class=So|first=Jason|last=McAddley|pos=WR|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=15|class=So|first=Freddie|last=Milons|pos=WR|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=60|class=Sr|first=Chris|last=Samuels|pos=T|link=y}}\n| defensive_players=\n{{American football roster/Player|num=24|class=Jr|first=Tony|last=Dixon|dab=Tony Dixon (American football)|pos=DB|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=97|class=Sr|first=Cornelius|last=Griffin|pos=DT|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=98|class=Sr|first=Reggie|last=Grimes|pos=DT|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=23|class=So|first=Reggie|last=Myles|pos=DB|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=11|class=So|first=Saleem|last=Rasheed|pos=LB|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|num=88|class=Jr|first=Kenny|last=Smith|pos=DT|link=y}}\n| special_teams_players=\n\n}}\n{{American football roster/Footer|roster_url=http://tidentenn.com/1999FootballRoster.htm\n| head_coach = *[[Mike DuBose]]\n| asst_coach = \n| accessdate=\n}}\n\n==Game summaries==\n\n===Vanderbilt===\n{{See also|1999 Vanderbilt Commodores football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#20 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=7\n|R4=14\n|Home=Commodores\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=10\n|H4=0\n}}\n[[Shaun Alexander]] scored the final two touchdowns in the 4th quarter to rally Alabama to a season opening road win over Vanderbilt.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Houston===\n{{See also|1999 Houston Cougars football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=Cougars\n|R1=3\n|R2=0\n|R3=7\n|R4=0\n|Home='''#21 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=10\n|H2=7\n|H3=6\n|H4=14\n}}\nAlabama would go over 500 yards of offense for just the second time in the Mike Dubose era and win convincingly over Houston. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Louisiana Tech===\n{{See also|1999 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''Bulldogs'''\n|R1=6\n|R2=6\n|R3=3\n|R4=14\n|Home=#18 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=3\n|H3=15\n|H4=10\n}}\nBack-up quarterback Brian Stallworth would find Sean Cangelosi in the end zone with two seconds left to upset Alabama for the second time in three years. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Arkansas===\n{{See also|1999 Arkansas Razorbacks football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=#14 Razorbacks\n|R1=10\n|R2=3\n|R3=8\n|R4=7\n|Home='''Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=7\n|H2=7\n|H3=14\n|H4=7\n}}\nDespite turning the football over six times, Alabama would manage to hold on and upset #14 Arkansas at Bryant-Denny Stadium. This would be the first time under Mike Dubose Alabama beat a ranked opponent.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Florida===\n{{See also|1999 Florida Gators football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#21 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=3\n|R2=10\n|R3=6\n|R4=14\n|R5=7\n|Home=#3 Gators\n|H1=7\n|H2=0\n|H3=15\n|H4=11\n|H5=6\n}}\nThe Crimson Tide snapped No. 3 Florida's 30-game winning streak at The Swamp on Saturday when Chris Kemp got a second chance on an extra-point attempt in overtime and drilled it.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Ole Miss===\n{{See also|1999 Ole Miss Rebels football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#11 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=10\n|R2=7\n|R3=10\n|R4=3\n|Home=#22 Rebels\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=10\n|H4=7\n}}\nDespite having a 27-7 lead midway through the third quarter, Alabama had to hold on late to beat Ole Miss. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Tennessee===\n{{See also|1999 Tennessee Volunteers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#5 Volunteers'''\n\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=7\n|R4=7\n|Home=#10 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=7\n|H3=0\n|H4=0\n}}\nFor the first time since 1930, the [[Third Saturday in October]] would be in Tuscaloosa. Despite having the largest crowd ever to watch a football game in the state of Alabama to date, The Crimson Tide could not generate enough offense to beat Tennessee. This gave the Volunteers their fifth win in a row against Alabama.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Southern Miss===\n{{See also|1999 Southern Miss Golden Eagles football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road= #20 Golden Eagles\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=0\n|R4=7\n|Home='''#14 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=10\n|H2=10\n|H3=15\n|H4=0\n}}\nBehind the Alabama defense who would hold Southern Miss to -13 yards rushing, Alabama would generate enough points with a pick six and a punt return to beat Southern Miss for the eight year in a row. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===LSU===\n{{See also|1999 LSU Tigers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=Tigers\n|R1=7\n|R2=0\n|R3=7\n|R4=3\n|Home='''#12 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=10\n|H3=13\n|H4=0\n}}\nThe 1999 version of a Goal Line stand as Alabama would deny LSU quarterback Josh Booty of a potential game winning touchdown run by knocking him down six inches short of the end zone to win.  \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Mississippi State===\n{{See also|1999 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road=#8 Bulldogs\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=0\n|R4=0\n|Home='''#11 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=3\n|H2=7\n|H3=3\n|H4=6\n}}\nWith the help of three Mississippi State interceptions, Alabama would end their three game losing streak to the Bulldogs and be one win away from winning the SEC West. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Auburn===\n{{See also|1999 Auburn Tigers football team}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''#8 Crimson Tide '''\n|R1=6\n|R2=0\n|R3=2\n|R4=20\n|Home=Tigers\n|H1=0\n|H2=14\n|H3=0\n|H4=3\n}}\n[[Shaun Alexander]] scored all three of Alabama touchdowns in the forth quarter as the Crimson Tide rallied back for the second year in a row to beat Auburn. This would also be the first time Alabama won at [[Jordan-Hare Stadium]]. With the win, Alabama clinched the SEC West for the first time since 1996. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Florida===\n{{See also|1999 Florida Gators football team|1999 SEC Championship Game}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Title=[[SEC Championship Game]]\n|Road=#5 Gators\n|R1=7\n|R2=0\n|R3=0\n|R4=0\n|Home= '''#7 Crimson Tide'''\n|H1=0\n|H2=12\n|H3=3\n|H4=19\n}}\nAlabama used 34 unanswered points to beat Florida for the second time in 1999. This would be the Crimson Tide's first [[SEC Championship]] since 1992. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Michigan===\n{{See also|1999 Michigan Wolverines football team|2000 Orange Bowl}}\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Title=[[Orange Bowl]]\n|Road='''#8 Wolverines'''\n|R1=0\n|R2=7\n|R3=21\n|R4=0\n|R5=7\n|Home= #5 Crimson Tide\n|H1=0\n|H2=14\n|H3=14\n|H4=0\n|H5=6\n}}\nDespite holding a 14 point lead in the third quarter, Alabama could not hold on and would lose in Overtime on a missed extra point by Ryan Pflugner. \n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1999 Southeastern Conference football season|Alabama]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football seasons]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1999 in sports in Alabama|Alabama Crimson Tide football]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "la